{
  "duration": 72.77,
  "text": "Every stoic geometry problem comes down to one formula. Mose equals mass divided by molar mass. N equals m over capital M. And the easiest way to remember it, the triangle, draw a triangle, put mass at the top. Mose, bottom left. Mola, mass bottom right. Cover what you want. And you can see the formula. Want moles? Cover N. You see mass over molar mass. Want mass? Cover M. You see moles times molar mass. Want molar mass? Cover M. Mass divided by moles. Let's use it. Question. How many moles in 24 grams of magnesium? Step one, molar mass of magnesium from the periodic table. 24 grams per mole. Step two, plug into the triangle. N equals 24 divided by 24. That's one mole. Done. Another one. How many moles in 11 grams of CO2? Mola mass of CO2 is 44. 11 divided by 44 equals 0.25 moles. Once you master this triangle, you can solve any mass to mole conversion. And that's most of your exam.",
